  "prompt": "If investment bankers are so rich then why doesn't everybody become one?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why not everyone becomes an investment banker:\n\n1. High barriers to entry\n- Requires top-tier university degrees (often from Ivy League or similar)\n- Extremely competitive selection process\n- Needs strong academic performance and networking skills\n\n2. Challenging work environment\n- Very long working hours (often 80-100 hours per week)\n- High stress levels\n- Intense performance pressure\n- Limited work-life balance\n\n3. Specific skill requirements\n- Strong quantitative and analytical skills\n- Advanced mathematical and financial knowledge\n- Excellent communication and presentation abilities\n- Ability to handle high-pressure situations\n\n4. Not everyone is suited to the job\n- Requires specific personality traits\n- Demands constant competition and performance\n- Not everyone enjoys or can handle the intense corporate culture\n\n5. Limited positions\n- Only a small number of investment banking roles exist\n- Not everyone who wants to enter can be hired\n\n6. Significant educational investment\n- Expensive university degrees\n- Often requires additional certifications\n- Potentially large student loan debt\n\n7. Emotional and mental toll\n- High burnout rates\n- Potential negative impact on mental health\n- Sacrificing personal life for career\n\nWhile investment banking can be financially rewarding, it's not a universally attractive or achievable career path for everyone.",
